         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [The chariot driver Chandaka] seized [the horse] Kanthaka. This Kanthaka ... because of the separation from [his] master ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... with the head letting rain burning tears, he began to (bow towards) the feet of the Bodhisattva ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having stretched [his] golden-colored arm [and] having put [his] hand provided with webbing on the head of Kanthaka, the (Bodhi)sattva (says) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[you] ought to be full of suffering and this is your animal birth. As you (pay homage?) to me because of that ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(after) having (obtained) myself the dignity of Buddhahood, I (will) pull you out of the mud of the Saṃsara ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… having (attained) the Buddha rank, then I will pull you out of this saṃsāra swamp … (Georges-Jean Pinault, p.c.)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>669</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having made ... before, [the horse or the chariot driver Chandaka] began to go to [the city] Kapilavastu. Again and again he kept looking (back) desperately ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having become weak, being disturbed, tripping, he kept going calling the Bodhisattva. Thereupon ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they brought. ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">they emitted (the news [of the return of the horse]) out from the city of (Kapi)lavastu far over the earth: "This is the most noble among horses."</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">The horse Kanthaka, having seen the garden Nyagrodhārāma, ... loudly (?) (in the) middle of ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">having seen the city of Kapilavastu, going [slowly] step by step because of suffering ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the whole city of Kapilavastu was full of (joy). Then (in) the city of Kapilavastu (the news was heard:)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">"The lord Sarvārthasiddha has turned back." Thereupon the people readily ran, ministers, princess(es), ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">"Sarvārthasiddha (is not there)." Then [a crowd of women] beginning with Gopikā Yaśodharā being confused by the sorrowful (news) ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">Lalitavistara, p. 231, 13-232,6</note><note type="remarks">Complete left part of a leaf with the string hole, PK NS 350 makes a perfect joint on the right side. In the first line of the verso side material from another fragment seems to have been glued over the writing in some cases, which makes the reading difficult.</note><note type="remarks">Information as to the provenance of the PK AS 15 fragments is entirely lost, but PK NS 350 has the expedition code DA.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">The complex <hi>niyātun</hi> does not have the shape of a regular Tocharian word; one may think of a loan, perhaps referring to horse's ornamental harness.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">In the complex <hi>wekwe ·rāna</hi> we can isolate <hi>wek</hi> referring to the cry of the horse. One may consider to set up an adverb <hi>wekwe</hi> "loudly". <hi>·rāna</hi> should be the complement of the adverb <hi>ywārc</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p><label>other</label>For the Sanskrit parallel cf. the translation by <bibl><title corresp="ref:waldschmidt1929"/><citedRange>111-113</citedRange></bibl>. In contrast to the Sanskrit version which has a dialogue between the Bodhisattva and the driver Chandaka this one focusses rather on the fate of the horse. The Tocharian text has been partly translated by <bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1953"/><citedRange>283-284</citedRange></bibl> lines a 6 and a 7 also in <bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1964"/><citedRange>240-241 fn. 17</citedRange></bibl> with a partial transcription. Cited in <bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1958"/><citedRange>14, 49, 97, 184, 206</citedRange></bibl>. </p>
         </div>
